{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565796"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.15,0.29,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11197"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84521"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"3077"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30654"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his fitness to work as a carpenter. He was diagnosed with Parkinson\u0027s disease eight months ago and takes levodopa-carbidopa. He reports increasing difficulty with fine motor tasks and occasional tremor in his right hand, particularly when tired. He works full-time in residential construction, frequently using power tools and working at heights. He has no other medical conditions and takes no other medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His vital signs are within normal limits. He has a mild right-sided resting tremor and rigidity. His gait is slightly slow but steady. Mini-Mental State Examination score is 29/30.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate occupational recommendation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate cessation of all work duties","Continue current duties with three-monthly reviews","Transfer to office-based administrative role","Restricted duties with no power tool use","Modified duties with increased supervision"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents an early-stage Parkinson\u0027s disease patient whose symptoms are beginning to affect his occupational function. The key considerations are workplace safety and the progressive nature of the condition, balanced against maintaining employment and independence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModified duties with increased supervision\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most appropriate balance between safety and maintaining employment. This allows continued work while ensuring safety through appropriate oversight and task modification. The patient can still utilise his skills and experience while having additional support for more challenging tasks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cessation of all work duties\u003C/strong\u003E is too extreme at this stage, as the patient\u0027s symptoms are mild and controlled with medication. Complete work cessation could negatively impact the patient\u0027s psychological well-being and financial situation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestricted duties with no power tool use\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive given the current level of symptoms. While some power tools may need to be avoided, a blanket ban is unnecessary if appropriate supervision and safety measures are in place.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current duties with three-monthly reviews\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide sufficient safety measures given the patient\u0027s work involves heights and power tools. The presence of tremor and fine motor difficulties requires more immediate workplace modifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to office-based administrative role\u003C/strong\u003E is premature and represents an unnecessary career change at this stage. The patient\u0027s skills and experience as a carpenter can still be utilised with appropriate modifications and support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key is to implement workplace modifications that maintain safety while preserving the patient\u0027s ability to work in their chosen profession. Regular reassessment is essential as Parkinson\u0027s disease is progressive, and work duties may need further modification over time.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parkinson\u0027s disease symptoms significantly impact occupational function, requiring early workplace modifications and support.","Regular assessment of cognitive function and manual dexterity is essential for workplace safety in Parkinson\u0027s disease.","Occupational health assessments should focus on both motor and non-motor symptoms of Parkinson\u0027s disease."],"references":["ParkinsonNet/NPF. Guidelines for Occupational Therapy in Parkinson\u0027s Disease Rehabilitation. 2011. Available at: https://www.parkinsonnet.nl/app/uploads/sites/3/2019/11/ot_guidelines_final-npf__3_.pdf","Parkinson\u0027s Foundation. Occupational Therapy and PD. Available at: https://www.parkinson.org/library/fact-sheets/occupational-therapy","Tofani M, Ranieri A, Fabbrini G, Berardi A, Pelosin E, Valente D, et al. Efficacy of occupational therapy interventions on quality of life in patients with Parkinson\u0027s disease: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Mov Disord. 2020 Oct;35(10):1587-1597. doi: 10.1002/mds.28101."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84521"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-07T14:36:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T14:37:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11197"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"dat